  "summary": "Hastings conveys Poirot's message to Norton, noting Norton's hesitation when Hastings asks if he has disclosed his discovery to anyone else. Later, Hastings encounters Elizabeth Coleridge on a grassy hill. During their conversation, Hastings expresses sadness regarding bad news about an old friend, implying that Poirot's health may be failing. Elizabeth discusses her loneliness and her relationship with Stephen Norton, but she becomes distressed when mentioning her sister, Maggie. Elizabeth believes Maggie is a criminal or a murderer, but Hastings asserts that Maggie did not kill her father and promises to prove her innocence.\n\nHastings then meets Boyd Carleton near the mansion. Carleton, who is moving to Nayton, expresses his dislike for the house's ominous atmosphere and suggests that Dr. Franklin might be responsible for his wife Barbara's death, noting that Franklin is indifferent and obsessed with his career. Carleton reveals that Cleven Nurse, who has unexpectedly returned to stay for the night, provided him with information and has long disliked Franklin. Hastings remains skeptical, reminding Carleton that Nurse's evidence helped secure a suicide verdict for Mrs. Franklin and that Poirot saw her holding a laboratory bottle. As Captain Alton approaches, Hastings reflects on the difficulty of investigating a suspect who lacks a clear motive. Finally, Hastings notes that while he has faith in Poirot's eventual victory, Poirot has expressed personal uncertainty by mentioning the possibility of something happening to him.",
